node.title: Police fear for baby reportedly left in Sydney coffee shop with $200 cash
node.alt: a baby in a bib looking up
node.description: The Family Court and AFP have gone public about the case of a missing baby who was reportedly left in the care of a woman in a Sydney coffee shop.
node.content:
["The Family Court and Australian Federal Police have made the unusual decision to go public about a missing baby who was left at a Sydney coffee shop earlier this year.", "Hoang Vinh Le, who is 17 months old, has not been seen since May when his parents say they gave him to a woman they met at coffee shop along with $200 cash to care for him.", "The parents have identified the woman as \"Kathy Nguyen\"\u00a0but authorities have been unable to find this person or verify whether they actually exist.", "Vinh's parents, Hoang Thanh Le and Lyn Kim Do, removed him from the care of his grandmother in Canberra on April 2.", "Just weeks later, the court made a recovery order for Vinh to be returned to the care of his grandmother but that order has not been complied with.", "The parents were arrested on May 20 however Vinh has not been located despite police efforts.", "The AFP says the parents have not provided sufficient details to enable the police to identify the person they say is caring for Vinh and authorities are concerned for his welfare.", "", "
Hoang Vinh Le with his mother Lyn Kim Do.(Supplied: AFP)
", "They say Vinh was last seen at a medical practice in the\u00a0Canberra suburb of O\u2019Connor on April 9 and was put into a silver\u00a0ISUZU MU-X 4WD with the NSW registration CF72YI.", "Since then, police\u00a0say, Vinh could have been in any of the following areas of NSW: Cabramatta, Bankstown, Liverpool, West Wyalong, Temora and Wagga Wagga.", "The AFP says anyone who is knowingly withholding information about the welfare or whereabouts of Vinh may be contributing to an offence.", "Anyone who has any information is asked to contact Crime Stoppers.", "The court recently made an order to allow the media to publish Vinh's identity in an attempt to receive public assistance on the case.", "Generally any information that identifies any person who is party to family law proceedings is unlawful."]
